\begin_layout Plain Layout
Which is not to say the concept of differential rent is completely worthless.
 In other contexts it may in fact be quite useful.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The dogma of a fixed, permanent supply of land appears as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

common sense
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 assertions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "135"
key "christophers2016forreal"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "806"
key "elden2010landterrain"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "334"
key "harvey2006thelimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "591"
key "li2014whatis"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 .
 Some authors allow for a 
\emph on
socially
\emph default
 variable supply of land embedded in a larger, fixed 
\emph on
physical
\emph default
 supply of land.
 For example, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "persky1988arather"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 model a situation in which the total supply of land is fixed, but monopolistic
 landowners hold land back from the market, letting some land sit vacant,
 in order to realize monopoly rents.
 Still others, like 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "32"
key "park2011spatial"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, seem willing to think of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

land itself as a product
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 but still insist that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

the supply of land is naturally limited
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 so that land may be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generally assumed to be i a different category of product from others.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In a review of 19th century concepts of rent, 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
after "17"
key "larmour1979theconcept"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 describes more variation than contemporary writers lead us to think.
 He points out that Ricardo did write of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

original and indestructable powers of the soil,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a notion that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

comes to shipwreck on the question of mines,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which are exhaustible by nature.
 But Ricardo's notion of an extensive margin implies variability in the
 supply of land.
 Among the marginalists, like Walras, Alfred Marshall called land 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

a free gift of nature,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


